WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.080
Our penultimate speaker is Andrew Gard, who will be talking about teaching and learning

00:00:04.080 --> 00:00:06.560
data science in the era of AI.

00:00:06.560 --> 00:00:11.160
What a really unique point in time in the history of the development of data science

00:00:11.160 --> 00:00:13.060
in the following sense.

00:00:13.060 --> 00:00:17.379
Nearly everyone practicing data science today learned to code prior to having ready access

00:00:17.379 --> 00:00:21.879
to AI, and yet we all have ready access to it now.

00:00:21.879 --> 00:00:26.160
On the other hand, nearly everyone learning data science today already has ready access

00:00:26.160 --> 00:00:30.280
to AI tools and is strongly incentivized to use it.

00:00:30.280 --> 00:00:31.280
I'm Andrew Gard.

00:00:31.280 --> 00:00:35.200
I'm a professor of mathematics at Lake Forest College, where I teach statistics in R to

00:00:35.200 --> 00:00:37.360
students at all different levels.

00:00:37.360 --> 00:00:42.560
I also maintain the popular RStats learning channel, Equitable Equations, like, share,

00:00:42.560 --> 00:00:43.560
subscribe.

00:00:43.560 --> 00:00:45.919
So I'm in the thick of all of this.

00:00:45.919 --> 00:00:50.279
I want to look at a question that I've asked students for many years in my introduction

00:00:50.279 --> 00:00:55.040
to data science with R classes, looking at the classic religious income data set and

00:00:55.040 --> 00:00:59.639
just asking them to give me a horizontal bar chart for income levels for one group

00:00:59.639 --> 00:01:00.639
of people in this set.

00:01:00.639 --> 00:01:02.919
And I want to use AI to approach this.

00:01:02.919 --> 00:01:06.760
I'm using GitHub Copilot, although it doesn't particularly matter if you're using a different

00:01:06.760 --> 00:01:09.839
tool like ChatGPT to do something like this.

00:01:09.839 --> 00:01:11.959
The comments that you're seeing here are my prompts.

00:01:11.959 --> 00:01:16.919
I've asked Copilot to pivot the data set and then produce that horizontal bar chart.

00:01:16.919 --> 00:01:20.959
And in a flash, I get a pretty passable thing right there.

00:01:20.959 --> 00:01:26.839
And if you think about this from the perspective of a new learner, your reaction might be,

00:01:26.839 --> 00:01:28.800
I don't even need to learn how to code.

00:01:28.800 --> 00:01:30.480
I don't need to know Pivot longer.

00:01:30.480 --> 00:01:33.879
This is not important anymore.

00:01:33.879 --> 00:01:38.559
And I want to throw a little cold water on this, or maybe at least lukewarm water with

00:01:38.559 --> 00:01:39.919
this cautionary tale.

00:01:39.919 --> 00:01:43.760
And what I've done here is to just modify the prompt very slightly, combining the two

00:01:43.760 --> 00:01:46.760
prompts I did before and taking out the word Pivot.

00:01:46.760 --> 00:01:50.519
And what's happened here is, of course, GitHub Copilot has failed.

00:01:50.519 --> 00:01:55.639
It has tried to do a ggplot using some variables that aren't actually in this data set.

00:01:55.639 --> 00:01:58.639
So what really went wrong here specifically?

00:01:58.639 --> 00:02:02.519
Why was one result awesome and the other silly?

00:02:02.519 --> 00:02:06.120
The main point I want to drive home today is that this is not just a problem of prompt

00:02:06.120 --> 00:02:07.339
engineering.

00:02:07.339 --> 00:02:11.479
In the second case here, we're seeing some important concepts that are missing from the

00:02:11.479 --> 00:02:13.080
prompter's brain.

00:02:13.080 --> 00:02:16.880
They don't have the vocabulary they need to say specifically what they want.

00:02:16.880 --> 00:02:20.800
The AI had to guess, and of course, it guessed wrong.

00:02:20.800 --> 00:02:25.119
Now this isn't surprising when we look back at the religious income data set.

00:02:25.119 --> 00:02:29.800
Nowhere in this set does the word income appear, or the word count.

00:02:29.800 --> 00:02:33.160
So that's information we brought to the table.

00:02:33.160 --> 00:02:37.720
While we're all hoping and expecting AI tools to get better and to hallucinate less over

00:02:37.720 --> 00:02:42.720
time, it's not realistic to expect it to be able to reliably guess at information that's

00:02:42.720 --> 00:02:46.919
not in the set and that we don't provide on our own.

00:02:46.919 --> 00:02:52.220
And this is why learning PivotLonger still really does bring value to the table.

00:02:52.220 --> 00:02:59.320
By learning tools like this, we learn important, I would say, essential data science ideas,

00:02:59.320 --> 00:03:04.279
like the difference between variables and observations, columns and rows.

00:03:04.279 --> 00:03:09.160
And while learning to code is not the only way to learn these essential concepts, it

00:03:09.160 --> 00:03:12.240
is the time-honored way.

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:16.119
Unfortunately, students are increasingly resistant to this technique.

00:03:16.119 --> 00:03:20.199
So how can we potentially update our pedagogy to reflect this new reality?

00:03:20.199 --> 00:03:25.220
Well, I don't exactly ask that same question anymore about the religious income data set,

00:03:25.220 --> 00:03:28.460
because I get a lot of AI-generated responses back.

00:03:28.460 --> 00:03:29.919
Some are great.

00:03:29.919 --> 00:03:31.419
Some are awful.

00:03:31.419 --> 00:03:32.800
Some are just plain hilarious.

00:03:33.800 --> 00:03:39.360
Instead, I'm asking things a little bit differently, providing students with that AI prompt and

00:03:39.360 --> 00:03:44.339
its output that did not work and asking questions like, why didn't this work?

00:03:44.339 --> 00:03:45.800
What information is missing?

00:03:45.800 --> 00:03:47.119
How can we provide it?

00:03:47.119 --> 00:03:50.000
Can you make this code actually work?

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:54.440
I think this has some important implications for all of us as continuous learners.

00:03:54.440 --> 00:03:58.679
We think about AI tools as things that are enhancing our productivity and allowing us

00:03:58.679 --> 00:04:00.160
to move faster.

00:04:00.160 --> 00:04:04.039
But when you're learning something new in data science and incorporating AI into your

00:04:04.039 --> 00:04:08.440
process, I want to urge you to slow down.

00:04:08.440 --> 00:04:13.479
Take some additional time right then and ask questions like, what's working here?

00:04:13.479 --> 00:04:14.880
What's not working here?

00:04:14.880 --> 00:04:17.100
How can I break this?

00:04:17.100 --> 00:04:22.839
Because of course, AI is not going to excuse us from learning to code at all.

00:04:22.839 --> 00:04:24.920
It's never going to replace human understanding.

00:04:24.920 --> 00:04:30.079
Of course, using it is not just an immediate path to failure.

00:04:30.200 --> 00:04:34.320
Since I haven't been gonged yet, I'll say really quickly that Equitable Equations brings

00:04:34.320 --> 00:04:39.200
a human-first perspective to the teaching of data science, R programming, and machine

00:04:39.200 --> 00:04:40.200
learning.

00:04:40.200 --> 00:04:43.519
As my fellow educators head back to the classroom in the next couple of weeks, I hope it's a

00:04:43.519 --> 00:04:46.239
free resource that can bring you a little bit of additional value.

00:04:46.239 --> 00:04:47.279
Thanks, everybody.

